<p>Not just for Ruby this time. This applies to pretty much every programming language under the sun.</p>

<p>Don't use unnecessary control statements to determine whether you want to return true or false.</p>

<pre><code class="ruby">def foo
  if some_boolean && other_boolean
    return true
  else
    return false
  end
end</code></pre>

<p>You should do this instead:</p>

<pre><code class="ruby">def foo
  return some_boolean && other_boolean
end</code></pre>

<p>It's very very rare that I ever have to return an explicit <code class="ruby">true</code> or <code class="ruby">false</code>. This should be a warning sign.</p>

<p>Of course, in Ruby <a href="http://barkingiguana.com/2009/10/21/you-dont-need-to-return-explicitly">you don't need to return explicitly</a> so you should do this:</p>

<pre><code class="ruby">def foo
  some_boolean && other_boolean
end</code></pre>
